[section className:"article-body"]

***TLDR: Currency exchange rate fluctuations affect most non-US students at Minerva to varying degrees. Long-term currency devaluation has significantly raised tuition prices for students with depreciating home currencies. Minerva's financial aid packages do not adjust to short-term currency devaluation, which forces students with home currencies prone to sudden devaluation to shoulder higher family contribution costs. There are several strategies for vulnerable students to manage the risk of currency devaluation, such as paying in installments, purchasing or earning USD, and futures contracts. Still, these strategies are not always viable or place additional burdens on students who are at risk of the effects of home currency devaluation.***
[hr /]
*(Click [a href:"https://jasenlo123.github.io/jasenlo123-The-Minerva-Quest---Forex/" target:"_blank"]underlines[/a] to visit links. Hover over [div className:"tooltip"]highlights[span className:"tooltiptext"]Instructions for navigating this interactive![/span][/div] for inline annotations.)*

According to [a href:"https://gist.github.com/emmastiefel/c891ff0910a253b1343259c5f27510bd" target:"_blank"]data[/a] provided by Teri Cannon, Minerva's Chief Student Affairs and Operations Officer, at least 77 nationalities and 66 currencies are represented in the Minerva student body. **That's a lot of different currencies.** 

Minerva students pay tuition in United States dollars (USD), but the actual value of tuition changes every second because of changes in currency exchange rates [div className:"tooltip"] (forex) [span className:"tooltiptext"] [b]forex[/b] stands for foreign exchange, which is used interchangably with currency exchange. [b]forex[/b] is a handy abbreviation that is used in this article. [/span][/div]. The value of a currency relative to all other currencies changes according to how much people want a particular currency.

