h [div className:"tooltip"]approximations[span className:"tooltiptext"] The data are estimates because of forex conversion fees are not taken into account, inflation measures prices of goods that do not always match up with changes in wages, while end-of-year forex rates were used for currency conversion even though tuition is usually due in the June/July (Fall) and November/December (Spring). [/span][/div].



The estimated data supports Chaves' claim that **her tuition cost almost doubled between 2017 and 2020. A full year of tuition in Brazillian real increased from $24,450 in 2017 to a frightening $36,891 in 2020 (in [div className:"tooltip"]real[span className:"tooltiptext"] A [b]real[/b] value is one which has been adjusted for inflation, enabling comparison of quantities as if the prices of goods had not changed on average. Changes in value in [b]real [/b]terms therefore exclude the effect of inflation.  [/span][/div] 2017 USD terms).** The incredible [div className:"tooltip"]cost increase[span className:"tooltiptext"] A contributor to the [b]cost increase[/b] is the nominal price increase of Minerva fees, which went up from 6% from $24,500 in 2017 to $25,950 in 2019. However, since we adjust for inflation, the dominant force behind real [b]cost differences[/b] across currencies are forex rates between years rather than the nominal increase in fees. Good to know that Minerva fees hasn't increased much in real terms, staying around $24,400 to $25,000 between 2017 to 2020 in 2017 USD![/span][/div] for students using consistently weakening currencies is troubling, especially for those whose families do not have savings in USD or depend on their income in their home currencies to afford the student's expected family contribution. A [div className:"tooltip"]hypothetical[span className:"tooltiptext"] It is also important to note that students who use the same currency are not necessarily affected in the same way, as Minerva students come from diverse socioeconomic backgrounds. A limitation of this investigation is that the data is only performed at a currency-level. This currency-level analysis neglects an individual's socioeconomic context, given specific forex shifts. [/span][/div] student paying for the Fall20 and Spring21 semesters at the end of the 2020 calendar year entirely in Argentine Peso, Turkish Lira, or Brazillian Real would have paid upwards of $33,000, while a student paying in USD would have only paid approximately $24,500. 
