[section className:"article-body"]
Fortunately, students affected by long-term currency devaluation may receive financial aid in scholarships and work-study wages in USD. However, even if the student paid a substantial portion of their Minerva costs in USD, the remaining amount would still be prohibitively expensive in their home currency. 

An additional implication is that **if students from countries with weak currencies have taken on student debt, they are more or less obliged to find employment in the United States** (or another country with a strong currency). It will be much harder to service loans if their wages from a job at home are paid to them in such a weak currency than to service loans using earnings in USD. 

[/section]

[section className:"article-body"]
[div className:'hed']Short-term Currency Fluctuations[/div]
Minerva's current financial aid system does not account for short term currency fluctuations that could put students in a difficult financial position. Financial aid packages are released in March, whereas term bill payments are due in July and November for the fall and spring semesters. The value of some particularly volatile currencies could change drastically in the time between these dates, to the point that the family contribution outlined in a financial aid package might be an entirely different amount of money by the time payments are due. Between March 2020 and November 2020, the Argentine Peso and Turkish Lira [div className:"tooltip"]depreciated significantly[span className:"tooltiptext"] Depreciation occured in previous years for these two specific currencies too. [/span][/div], which led to a price increase of Argentine and Turkish students' fees by 29% and 21% respectively. 

[/section]

[FullWidth]
  [Flourish visualisation:"5006590" /]
[/FullWidth]

[section className:"article-body"]
One of the financial aid [a href:"https://www.minervaquest.com/2020/10/10/shipping-financial-aid-packages-from-a-us-based-university-to-a-global-student-body/" target:"_blank"] Day of Action[/a] demands was that students receive "an expected family contribution in both USD and the student's home currency" in their financial aid packages. Such a policy would [div className:"tooltip"]shield [span className:"tooltiptext"] If a student's currency weakened between March and November, they wouldn't have to pay more because they would pay with the forex rate in March instead of the forex rate in November. In contrast, those with stronger currencies wouldn't get to pay less by taking advantage of their relatively stronger currency. [/span][/div] students from currency fluctuations. The Minerva senior team [a href:"https://d1c2gz5q23tkk0.cloudfront.net/assets/uploads/2924499/asset/Minerva_Response_to_Student_Demands_-_April_16_2020_%281%29.pdf?1587058414" target:"_blank"]concluded[/a] that they "cannot assume all of the risk and shield students and parents entirely from currency fluctuations as this would make financial planning and budgeting unduly hard and more expensive." 
[br /]
[br /]
[br /]
[div className:'hed']Coping Mechanisms?[/div]
How can students at-risk of home currency devaluation cope with these forex rate changes? The Quest interviewed Niko Pelka, Minerva's Chief Finance Officer to discuss potential avenues students could use to alleviate the effects of long and short term currency devaluation. The Quest also spoke to Minerva students who have tried to reduce their forex-related financial burden using unorthodox strategies.
[hr /]

[text className:"dek"]
[u]Financial Aid Adjustment[/u]
[/text]
Pelka told the Quest that Minerva's financial aid system attempts to address long-term currency fluctuations when deciding on how much a student’s family is required to pay. Minerva's financial aid analysis takes "large currency swings over the past 12 months" into consideration, along with other factors such as national economic performance and family circumstances. Additionally, financial aid application figures are converted into USD using the forex rate at the time of the application, which means that financial aid package calculations should reflect a student's financial circumstance if forex rates had significantly altered their conditions. 

//Turkey depreciation video
[Aside]
[iframe width:"375" height:"300" src:"https://www.youtube.com/embed/UW6WSWyfMBs"]
[/iframe]
[text className:"caption"]
Source: [a href:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UW6WSWyfMBs" target:"_blank"] AltSimplified[/a]. This article doesn't go into the complicated reasons behind why currencies depreciate. For those curious, this Youtube video explains why the Turkish lira has weakened since 2018. [/text]
[/Aside]

However, numerous students offered testimonies against the financial aid system's efficacy in addressing long-term currency devaluation. Students from countries with devaluated currencies such as Turkey and South Africa told the Quest that their financial aid package rarely changed between years despite considerable changes in the values of the Turkish lira and the South African rand. 

Bella Buchanan (M'21) from South Africa mentioned that even though she received more financial aid for this calendar year, it was still far from enough. Both her parents had lost their jobs, and the South African rand had depreciated significantly. She suspects that the financial aid calculations had overlooked the South African rand's depreciation. Buchanan tried but failed to appeal for more aid as Minerva deferred students to seek out financial relief through remote study options and thus did not accept financial aid appeals this financial aid cycle.

[text className:"dek"]
[u]More USD Please?[/u]
[/text]

Although forex rates are notoriously [a href:"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Why-are-exchange-rates-so-difficult-to-predict-Wang/4ba0f737896a8f3714e7f16056449883d909b3ce" target:"_blank"]difficult to predict[/a], for students anticipating their home currency's continuous depreciation, having USD on-hand for future term bill payments sooner would likely save fees in the long run. 

Purchasing sums of USD would require liquid assets that some students and their families might not have readily available. For students who do not have substantive savings in any currency or assets, purchasing USD whenever they have available funds creates financial burdens that may alter their lifestyle. Otherwise, students could find more USD by finding employment or internships that pay in USD rather than in their home currencies. 

These dynamics underscore the importance of Minerva's work-study program as a source of USD for students with weak home currencies. In the cases where work-study income might not be enough because of a sudden home currency depreciation, students may have to find additional USD income. Given the rigours of Minerva's academics and how Minerva's global rotation program takes students away from the United States, the search for USD search can be arduous. This Quest [a href:"https://www.minervaquest.com/2020/07/16/financial-aid-student-profiles-tessa-owens/" target:"_blank"]profile[/a] of Tessa Owens (M'21) documents the struggles of working more than 20 hours a week during the school semester. 

[text className:"dek"]
[u]Installments via Payment Plans[/u]
[/text]
According to Pelka, 10-15% of Minerva students opt for payment plans to pay for term bill balances owed to Minerva in installments. Students prefer installments for a variety of different reasons. One such reason is waiting out a period of poor forex rates. 

Buchanan told the Quest that her family had opted for Minerva's payment plan option, hoping that the South African Rand would appreciate against the USD within half a year. For instance, the term bill for the Fall20 semester was due on July 15th, 2020. The payment plan would divide a student's payment into three installments due on 15th July 2020, 15th September 2020, and 15th November 2020. If a student's home currency appreciates between these dates, a student might save on their term bill.
 
[/section]


//installment
[FullWidth]
  [Flourish visualisation:"5030765" /]
[/FullWidth]
[section className:"article-body"]


However, Minerva charges students a [div className:"tooltip"]service fee[span className:"tooltiptext"] For example, a payment plan on a term bill of [b]$30,000 USD[/b] would end up costing the student [b]$31,200 USD[/b], ignoring any changes in currency exchange rates. [/span][/div] of 4% of their term bill to use a payment plan. Pelka told the Quest that the fee is a simple compromise to cover Minerva’s costs from not having the cash from the student's contribution available at-hand and to track multiple separate payments. He acknowledged that the service fee favors students with low family contribution amounts and burdens students with high contribution amounts.

Additionally, opting for a payment plan runs the additional risk that if one's home currency depreciates even more each installment becomes more expensive in the home currency. [div className:"tooltip"]Backtesting[span className:"tooltiptext"] [b]Backtesting[/b] results are included in the methodological notes are at the bottom of this article! [/span][/div] a payment plan strategy for the Fall20 billing period reveals that this strategy would have resulted in a cheaper bill for only students whose home currency is the Mexican Peso. **The installment strategy is not only a dangerous gamble but one that is highly unlikely to succeed.**
 
If a student's home currency is weak and they are short of USD when the term bill is due but have a source of income in the United States, it might be worth the 4% fee to service installments with their USD earnings rather than purchase USD using their home currency. A finding that surfaced after digging into the viability of a payment plan strategy is that students who earn their school fees in increasingly weak home currencies should generally avoid taking a payment plan if possible. **If students are forced into paying in installments because they lack available funds, short-term currency devaluation and the 4% payment plan service fee are additional punitive costs to those already in financial trouble.**

[text className:"dek"]
[u]Futures Contracts[/u]
[/text]
Pelka told the Quest that Minerva cannot protect a student against short-term forex rate fluctuations, stating that currency price movements are risks that affect  not just students but Minerva too. "Everything we did in Europe last year became 15% more expensive compared to when we planned it. Minerva carries risks for in-country operations, while students carry the risk on the tuition side. Minerva does not see how we can absolve students of that risk," he said.  
 
//Future contract youtube video
[Aside]
[iframe width:"375" height:"300"
src:"https://www.youtube.com/embed/9BQr-vxwqJs"]
[/iframe]
[text className:"caption"]
Source: [a href:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9BQr-vxwqJs&feature=emb_logo" target:"_blank"] Concerning Reality[/a]. A short Youtube video that provides some intuition behind how futures contracts work. [/text]
[/Aside]

When asked how Minerva students could manage the risk of currency devaluation in lieu of protection on the part of Minerva, Pelka cautiously suggested forex [div className:"tooltip"]futures contracts[span className:"tooltiptext"] A [b]futures contract[/b] is a legal agreement to buy or sell a particular commodity asset, or security at a predetermined price at a specified time in the future. In this context, it's an agreement with some institution for them to trade USD for another currency at a predetermined forex rate. [/span][/div], to manage the risk of currency depreciation. However, he was quick to point out the [div className:"tooltip"]practical impossibility[span className:"tooltiptext"] Any ambitious business students who might want to try their hand at this problem?[/span][/div]for Minerva to purchase and keep track of multiple futures contracts, and the unlikelihood that Minerva students and their families would explore advanced trading instruments such as futures. 

 
The Quest also spoke to a Minerva professor familiar with futures contracts, who was also skeptical of their viability for managing forex risk. They stated that it is unlikely that students could secure futures at a reasonable price if their home currency is incredibly volatile or expected to depreciate further. **This would mean that the most vulnerable students to currency devaluations are charged the most should they protect themselves against depreciation risks with futures contracts.**

[text className:"dek"]
[u]Nuclear Option - Restructuring Payments[/u]
[/text]
Pelka notified the Quest that if a student does find themselves in dire financial straits, for whatever reason inclusive of currency devaluation, they should communicate their situation to Minerva because Minerva is ultimately interested in working out a solution.

In this situation, students may work out a personalised payment plan with Minerva, restructuring their payment by rescheduling payment dates or borrowing against their security deposit. According to Pelka, Minerva usually has the flexibility to restructure a payment. Unfortunately, because of [div className:"tooltip"]cash-flow[span className:"tooltiptext"] Minerva just doesn't have enough money to be owed money. Small institution, after all. [/span][/div] concerns, Minerva cannot restructure payments beyond a year or act as a lender of last resort. Furthermore, Pelka emphasised that the solution of restructuring payments is a nuclear option best avoided. While Minerva can restructure a few students' payments, they cannot afford to do so for most students since Minerva is highly dependent on student tuition to operate. 

[/section]


[section className:"article-body"]
[div className:'hed']Takeaways[/div]

* Long term currency devaluation significantly increases Minerva fees for students with consistently weakening home currencies. Though Minerva's financial aid accounts for currency depreciation, students have suggested otherwise.
* Lower-income students who do not hold savings in USD from countries with weak home currencies will most likely have to find a job in the United States to service student debt.
* Using installment payment plans to wait for short-term home currency appreciation, and purchasing futures contracts for USD are not viable strategies to protect oneself from currency devaluation.
* The 4% payment plan fee and short-term currency devaluation are serious financial burdens for students forced into installments. Those who anticipate further weakening of their home currency should avoid opting for payment plan installments if they plan to use earnings in their home currency to service installments if possible but could consider doing so if they earn in USD. 
[hr/]

These takeaways are likely common knowledge among students who are negatively affected by forex rates. **A thorough understanding of forex rates is crucial for all students to make informed financial decisions regarding their Minerva education cost.**

*When should I purchase USD to pay for the next term bill? Should I try to aim for a summer job at home or in the United States? Should I take on these student loans if I want to work a job at home after graduation? How much more or less do I pay if I opt for Minerva's payment plan?* 

Currency volatility data reveals that only a minority of currencies have their value [div className:"tooltip"]fixed[span className:"tooltiptext"] A [b]fixed[/b] exchange rate is a regime applied by a government or central bank that ties the country's official currency exchange rate to another country's currency. The purpose of a [b]fixed[/b] exchange rate system is to keep a currency's value stable. [/span][/div] to the USD. Thus, forex rates affect most non-American students at Minerva, although it is clear that students are affected by varying degrees. Students with home currencies that maintain a fixed exchange rate with the USD are not affected at all. As with many problematic issues facing the Minerva student community, the systemic consequences and dynamics of global inequalities affect some students more than others. Can the Minerva community accept this degree of experiential inequality between those positively and negatively affected by forex rate changes?

[/section]

