[section className:"article-body"]

**This report finds potential consequences for students who have experienced significant home currency depreciation to be staggering. Such students may have to take on more loans, find more employment, limit their post-graduation choices, sacrifice their quality of life and that of their families, and expend the effort to monitor and act upon currency exchange rates.**

The lack of viable strategies available to students who face home currency depreciation, combined with the limited flexibility on Minerva's part to adjust to such students' needs, demonstrate that the risks and consequences of home currency depreciation will continue to persist given Minerva's cosmopolitan demographics. 

Although no individual at Minerva is culpable for forex rate movements, to what extent is Minerva at fault for exposing, or failing to inform, students of such costly risks? Would an M′21 student from Argentina have second thoughts about attending Minerva if they understood that their education might cost approximately 30% more than they thought, and an implicit commitment to working in the United States? 


[/section]

//total
[FullWidth]
